<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="notes-islam">
  <title>Mathematics in the Islamic World (5.5)</title>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-Algebra-in-the-Islamic-World">
    <title>Algebra in the Islamic World</title>

    <p>
        I have decided to use the term <q>Islamic World</q> to describe the mathematics in areas of the world that were unified by a shared culture centered around the religion of Islam, much the same way as Europe in the Middle ages was unified by a common culture of Christianity. This doesn't mean that all the mathematicians in this region were Muslim; although most were. For example Qusta ibn Luqa (Costas son of Luke) was a 9th century Lebanese Christian mathematician who translated many Greek texts into Arabic including Diophantus' <em>Arithmetica</em>. The region that we will consider includes Arabia, Mesopotamia, the Levant, North Africa, Iran, Central Asia, and parts of Spain and Portugal. Some sources use the terms <term>Muslim</term> and <term>Arab</term> interchangably when referring to mathematicians of this time and place. This is incorrect because they were not all Arabs. 
    </p>

    <p>
      A quick note on reading Arabic names: A child in an Arabic family is given a name such as Thabit or Muhammad. After this comes a phrase meaning <q>son of</q> so Thabit ibn Muhammad means <q>Thabit son of Muhammad</q>. This can be extended further back such as Thabit ibn Muhammad ibn Ismail ibn Ibrahim, which goes back to the great grandfather. Later in life one may add a paternal name such as Abu Aladdin (father of Aladdin). At the end comes a name indicating a tribe or place of origin such as al-Harrani (the man from Harran). Finally there may also be a nickname at the end such as al-Rashid (the Orthodox). Putting this altogether and you could have a name Thabit ibn Muhammad ibn Ismail ibn Ibrahim abu Aladdin al-Harrani al-Rashid.
    </p>

    <p>
      The first Islamic mathematician we will examine is Al-Kharizmi. Muhammad ibn Musa Al-kharizmi was an Iranian Mathematician who studied at the House of Wisdom. The House of Wisdom was a large library and academy founded in Baghdad in the 8th century A.D. The scholars of the House of Wisdom translated Greek and Indian texts into Arabic, which preserved much of the knowledge of the ancient Greeks which had been lost in Europe. The translation of these Arabic texts to Latin was one of the causes of the Renaissance. Al-Khwarizmi is most famous for his textbook <em>Al-jabr wa'l muqabalah</em>, which is where our word <term>algebra</term> comes from. In addition our word <term>algorithm</term> comes from al-Kwwarizmi's name.
    </p>

    <p>
      Al-jabr is an arabic word meaning reunion of broken parts, or bonesetting, In his book Al-kharizmi uses the word al-jabr to refer to the process of adding a positive quantity to both sides of an equation to remove a negative quantity. For example if we are given the equation
      <md>
        4x= 9 - 2x
      </md>
      then adding <m>2x</m> to both sides to obtain 
      <md>
        6x=9
      </md>
      is an example of al-jabr.
    </p>

    <p>
      In his book, Al-kharizmi classified 6 types of equations. He referred to the unknown variable as the root and the constant as the number. His 6 types of equations are
     
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            roots equal squares: <m>bx = ax^2</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            roots equal numbers: <m>bx=c</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            squares equal numbers: <m>ax^2 = c</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            squares and roots equal numbers: <m>ax^2 + bx = c</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            roots and numbers equal squares: <m>bx + c = ax^2</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            squares and numbers equal roots: <m>ax^2 + c = bx</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
      Here <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, and <m>c</m> are positive integers. All 6 equations are special cases of quadratic equations.
    </p>

    <p>
      Al-Khwarizmi explains each of the examples in great detail. Let us consider in depth his example for <term>roots and squares equal to numbers</term>.
    </p>

    <blockquote>
      <p>
        For instance <q>one square, and ten roots of the same, amount to thirty-nine dirhems</q>; that is to say, what must be the square which, when increased by ten of its own roots, amounts to thirty-nine? The solution is this: you halve the number of the roots which in the present instance yields five. This you multiply by itself; the product is twenty-five. Add this to thirty-nine; the sum is sixty four. Now take the root of this, which is eight, and subtract from it half the number of the roots, which is five; the remainder is three. This is the root of the square which you sought for; the square itself is nine.
      </p>
    </blockquote>

    <p>
      This example, <m>x^2+10x = 39</m> appears frequently in Islamic works and early western works on algebra. Al-Khwarizmi doesn't stop with the solution of the problem. He continues to show using geometry why the solution method works.
    </p>

    <blockquote>
      <p>
        We have said enough so far as numbers are concerned, about the six types of equations. Now, however, it is necessary that we should demonstrate geometrically the truth of the same problems which we have explained in numbers. Therefore our first proposition is this, that a square and 10 roots equal 39 units. 
      </p>

      <p>
        The proof is that we construct a square of unknown sides, and let this square figure represent the square (second power of the unknown) which together with its root you wish to find. Let the square, then, be <m>ab</m> of which any side represents one root. When we multiply any side of his by a number (or numbers) it is evident that that which results from the multiplication will be a number of roots equal to the root of the same number (of the square). Since then ten roots were proposed with the square, we take a fourth part of the number ten and apply to each side of the square an area of equidistant sides, of which the length should be the same as the length of the square first described and the breadth <m>2 \frac{1}{2}</m>, which is a fourth part of <m>10</m>. Therefore four areas of equidistant sides are applied to the first square <m>ab</m>. Of each of these the length is the length of one root of the square <m>ab</m> and also the breadth of each is <m>2 \frac{1}{2}</m>, as we have just said. These now are the areas <m>c,d, e,f</m>. Therefore it follows from what we have said that there will be four areas having sides of unequal length, which are also regarded as unknown. The size of the areas in each of the four corners, which is found by multiplying <m>2\frac{1}{2}</m> by <m>2\frac{1}{2}</m>, completes that which is lacking in the larger or whole area. Whence it is [that] we complete the drawing of the larger area by the addition of the four products, each <m>2\frac{1}{2}</m> by <m>2\frac{1}{2}</m>; the whole of this multiplication gives <m>25</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        And now it is evident that the first square figure, which represents the square of the unknown [<m>x^2</m>] and the four surrounding areas [<m>10x</m>] make <m>39</m>. When we add <m>25</m> to this, that is, the four smaller squares which indeed are placed at the four angles of the square <m>ab</m>, the drawing of the larger square called <m>GH</m> is completed. Whence also the sum total of this is <m>64</m>, of which <m>8</m> is the root and by this is designated one side of the completed figure. Therefore when we subtract from <m>8</m> twice the fourth part of <m>10</m>, which is placed at the extremities of the larger square <m>GH</m> there will remain but <m>3</m>. Five being subtracted from <m>8</m>, <m>3</m> necessarily remains, which is equal to one side of the first square <m>ab</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        This <m>3</m> then expresses one root of the square figure, that is one root of the proposed square of the unknown and <m>9</m> the square itself. Hence we take half of <m>10</m> and multiply this by itself. We then add the whole product of the multiplication to <m>39</m>, that the drawing of the larger square <m>GH</m> may be completed; for the lack of the four corners rendered incomplete the drawing of the whole of this square. Now it is evident that the fourth part of any number multiplied by itself and then multiplied by four gives the same number as half of the number multiplied by itself. Therefore if half of the root is multiplied by itself, the sum total of this multiplication will wipe out, equal, or cancel out the multiplication of the fourth part by itself and then by <m>4</m>.
      </p>

        </blockquote>

      <p>
        The next great Islamic algebraist that we will consider is Omar Khayyam (1048-1131 A.D.) an Iranian mathematician and poet. His poetry became renowned throughout the English speaking world after it was translated into English in 1859 by Edward FitzGerald, who published it as <em>The Rubaiyat of Omar Khayyam</em>. Some of his poetry conveys a sceptical attitude towards religious faith and the medieval historian Al-Qifti wrote that Khayyam was indicted for impiety and went on a pilgrimage to Mecca to clear himself of charges of atheism. 
      </p>

      <p>
        As a mathematician, Omar Khayyam is most famous for his work on cubic equations. Following the example of Al-Khwarizmi, he set out to classify all types of cubic equations and ultimately to find a method for solving them. There are <m>27</m> types of cubic equations corresponding to the number of ways that an expression of the form
        <md>
          x^3+ax^2+bx+c = 0
        </md>

        can be written so that all coefficients are either positive or zero. For example as

        <md>
          x^3+bx = ax^2+c
        </md>

        (cubes and sides equal to squares and numbers). We can obtain this by allowing <m>a, b, </m> and <m>c</m> to be positive, negative, or zero. With three choices for each coefficient we get a total of <m>27</m> possibilities.
        
        
      </p>

      <p>
        Omar Khayyam enumerated these equations by counting how many non-zero terms occur. He excluded the case where no such coefficients occur (corresponding to <m>x^3 = 0</m>).
      </p>

      <p>
        There are six equations with only two non-zero terms. They are of the form <m>x^3+ax^2=0</m>, <m>x^3+bx=0</m>, or <m>x^3+c = 0</m> where none of <m>a,b,</m> or <m>c</m> are equal to zero. Khayyam regarded the first two types as being equivalent to quadratic equations, but included the positive and negative cases of the third type.
      </p>

      <p>
        There are twelve cases with exactly three non-zero terms. Khayyam regarded the four cases where <m>c=0</m> as equivalent to quadratic equations and solvable by known methods. This left him eight equations that are not equivalent to quadratic equations.
      </p>

      <p>
        Finally there are eight cases in which none of the coefficients are zero. None of these are equivalent to quadratic equations. Thus there are <m>18</m> types of cubic equations that cannot be reduced to quadratic equations. However some of these equations such as <m>x^3+ c = 0</m> where <m>c</m> is a positive number cannot have positive solutions, so Khayyam excluded four types for that reason. That left <m>14</m> types of cubic equations that must be solved.
      </p>

      <p>
        Khayyam solved these cubics equations with geometry instead of algebra. He wrote <q>Algebras are geometric facts which are proved by Propositions 5 and 6 of Book II of the Elements</q>. By this he meant that when solving an equation by algebra, the results obtained can also be proven using geometry. To understand Khayyam's work, let's first consider how a cubic equation can be obtained from the intersection of a circle and a parabola.
      </p>

      <p>
        Let the circle have equation <m>x^2+y^2-2xa = 0</m>; that is the circle has center <m>(a,0)</m> and radius <m>a</m>. We let the parabola have equation <m>x^2= by</m> so that it opens upward, is symmetric about the <m>y</m>-axis and has its vertex at the origin. In fact, the circle and parabola intersect at the origin. There is another point where the two curves intersect and we can solve for it by solving the system of equations using elimination. Substituting <m>y = x^2/b</m> into the equation of the circle, we get
        <md>
          x^2 + \left( \frac{x^2}{b} \right)^2 - 2xa = 0
        </md>
        which simplifies to 
        <md>
          x^4 + b^2x^2-2b^2ax = 0
        </md>
        By setting aside the point of intersection at the origin which corresponds to the factor <m>x=0</m> we are left wide a cubic equation in <m>x</m>.
        <md>
          x^3+b^2x - 2b^2a = 0
        </md>
        
      </p>

      <p>
        To connect this to a cubic equation of the form
        <md>
          x^3 + \alpha x - \beta = 0
        </md>
        we need to express <m>\alpha</m> and <m>\beta</m> in terms of <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>. Since <m>b^2 = \alpha</m>, <m> b = \sqrt{\alpha}</m> and since <m>2b^2a = \beta</m>, <m>a = \frac{\beta}{2\alpha}</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        However Khayyam had to show how to find <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> geometrically, so he had to give constructions for <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> in terms of the given lengths <m>\alpha</m> and <m>\beta</m>.
      </p>

    <p>
      Khayyam's method for solving the equation <m>x^3+ \alpha x - \beta = 0</m> is as follows. First he constructs a line <m>BC</m> with length <m>\dfrac{\beta}{\alpha}</m>. Next draw a second line <m>AB</m> with length <m>\sqrt{\alpha}</m> that is perpendicular to <m>BC</m>. He then constructs a parabola with vertex at <m>B</m> and parameter (distance from focus to directrix) equal to <m>\dfrac{\sqrt{\alpha}}{2}</m>
    </p>

    <p>
      Next he draws a semicircle on <m>BC</m>. This semicircle intersects the parabola at one point, which we call <m>D</m>. He then draws a line perpendicular to <m>BC</m> that passes through <m>D</m>. Let <m>E</m> be the point where that line intersects <m>BC</m>. Then <m>BE</m> is the line segment that solves the problem. That is, the length of <m>BE</m> is the value of <m>x</m> that solves the equation.
    </p>

    <p>
      Here is an alternative form of his method.
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            First sketch the parabola <m>y = \dfrac{1}{\sqrt{\alpha}}x^2</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Next draw a line segment on the <m>x</m> axis from the origin to <m>\frac{\beta}{\alpha}</m> and draw a semicircle on the line.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Locate the point where the semicircle and parabola intersect. The x coordinate of that point is the solution to the cubic equation.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>

    <p>
      Example: Use Khayyam's method to solve <m>x^3 + 4x=20</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      The intersection of the a circle and parabola is only used to solve equations of the form <m>x^3+ \alpha x - \beta = 0</m>. For other types of equations Khayyam used a different intersection to find the solution.
    </p>

    <table xml:id="omar-cubic-equations">2  <title>Omar Khayyam's Classification of Cubic Equations</title>3  <tabular>4    <col width="40%"/>5    <col width="60%"/>6 7    <row>8      <cell><m>Type (\alpha &gt; 0,\ \beta &gt; 0)</m></cell>9      <cell>Method</cell>10    </row>11 12    <row>13      <cell><m>x^3=\beta</m></cell>14      <cell>Intersection of 2 parabolas</cell>15    </row>16 17    <row>18      <cell><m>x^3+\alpha x=\beta</m></cell>19      <cell>Intersection of a circle and parabola</cell>20    </row>21 22    <row>23      <cell><m>x^3\pm\beta=\alpha x</m></cell>24      <cell>Intersection of a hyperbola and parabola</cell>25    </row>26 27    <row>28      <cell><m>x^3=\alpha x+\beta</m></cell>29      <cell>Intersection of 2 hyperbolas</cell>30    </row>31  </tabular>32</table>
  

    <p>
      In his introduction to cubic equations Khayyam wrote
    </p>

    <blockquote>
      <p>
        When, however, the object of the problem is an absolute number, neither we, nor any who are concerned with algebra, have been able to prove this equation--perhaps others who follow us will be able to fill in the gap--except when it contains only the first 3 degrees, namely the number, the thing and the square
      </p>
    </blockquote>

    <p>
      By absolute number, Khayyam means an algebraic solution instead of a geometrical one. Although he never found a way to solve all cubics algebraically, he did forsee that it would be possible.
    </p>
    
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-Trigonometry-in-the-Islamic-World">
    <title>Trigonometry in the Islamic World</title>
    
    <p>
      The sine and cosine functions were first invented in India but were transmitted to Europe via the mathematicians of the Islamic world. However, the Indians defined the sine function slightly differently than we do today. Their sine function was equal to the radius of the circle times the ratio between the opposite and hypotenuse of the angle. Islamic mathematicians first introduced the modern sine function with a circle of unit radius.
    </p>

    <p>
      Sine and cosine are basically Indian inventions, but the tangent function is uniquely the creation of Islamic mathematics. The 9th century Iranian astronomer Habash al-Hasib examined the length of the shadow of a unit rod when the sun was at various angles. The length <m>s</m> of the shadow cast by a horizontal rod is <m>\tan \alpha</m>, where <m>\alpha</m> is the angle of elevation of the sun above the horizon. The length <m>t</m> of the shadow cast by a vertical rod is <m>\cot \alpha</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Secant and Cosecant were rarely used in Islamic mathematics, but they do appear in a work by Iranian mathematician Abu al-Wafa in the 10th century. Al-Wafa also constructed a table of tangents and a sine table that was more accurate than previous sine tables. He did this in part by using a rule for calculating the sum or difference of 2 sines. In modern notation his rule (The angle addition formula for Sine) is
      <md>
        \sin (\alpha \pm \beta) = \sin \alpha \cos \beta \pm \cos \alpha \sin\beta
      </md>
      
    </p>

    <p>
      Al-Wafa described the formula thusly
    </p>

    <blockquote>
      <p>
        Multiply the sine of each of them by the cosine of the other, expressed in sixtieths, and we add the 2 products if we want the sine of the sum of the two arcs, but take the difference if we want the sine of the difference.
      </p>
    </blockquote>

    <p>
      The reference to the functions expressed in sixtieths shows that these calculations were carried out using fractions in base 60. This is because 60 has more factors than 10, so it is easier to work with fractions in base 60 than base 10.
    </p>

    <p>
      One of the great achievements of Islamic mathematicians were very accurate tables of sines. In order to make an accurate table of sines, it is imperative that we get a good approximation for <m>\sin 1^{\circ}</m>. Once we have such an approximation, we can use the sum formula to find the sines of any integer degree by adding the approximation for <m>\sin 1^{\circ}</m> multiple times. Approximating <m>\sin 1^{\circ}</m> is not easy, however. We will look at how this problem was approached by Islamic mathematicians.  
    </p>

    <p>
      One approach involved repeatedly applying the half angle formula, which was known to the Ancient Greeks
      <md>
        \sin \left (  \dfrac{\alpha}{2}\right ) = \pm \sqrt{\dfrac{1 - \cos \alpha}{2} }
      </md>
    </p>

    <p>
      First it can be shown that <m>\sin 72^{\circ} = \sqrt{\dfrac{5+\sqrt{5}}{8}}</m> and <m>\sin 60^{\circ}= \dfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2}</m>. Thus by using Al-Wafa's formula, one can determine <m>\sin 12^{\circ}</m>. By repeated application of the half-angle formula, one can approximate the values of the sines of angles of 6, 3, 1.5 and 0.75 degrees. 
    </p>

    <p>
      For small values of <m>\theta</m> <m>\sin \theta \approx \theta</m>. Thus we can approximate <m>\sin 1^{\circ}</m> by averaging the sines of 1.5 and 0.75 degrees. This procedure gives a close estimate for the sine of 1 degree, but it is not perfectly accurate because the average of the sine of 1.5 and 0.75 degrees while close, is not quite the sine of 1 degree.
    </p>

    <p>
      A second approach was developed by the Iranian Mathematician Al-Kashi based on cubic equations. Al-Kashi lived during the conquests of Tamerlane, during which there was widespread poverty. Al-Kashi himself lived in poverty for many years, but eventually was invited to work at the astronomy of Ulugh Beg.
    </p>

    <p>
      Timur the Lame (or Tamerlane) was a descendant of Genghis Khan, who conquered much of Central Asia and the Middle East in an attempt to restore Genghis Khan's empire. When he died his empire was divided among his successors and his grandson Ulugh Beg inherited the region of Transoxiana in central Asia in 1411 while still a teenager.
    </p>

    <p>
      Unlike his grandfather, Ulugh Beg's passion was not warfare but rather astronomy. He built a large observatory called the Ulugh Beg Observatory in Samarkand, which attracted a large number of astronomers and mathematicians including Al-Kashi. Ulugh Beg worked with the other astronomers to create a catalog of the stars. In 1438 they published the Zij-i Sultani, a catalog of 992 stars and their positions. This required precise trigonometric calculations. The astronomers also produced a table of sines and tangents with 8 decimal places of accuracy. They did this by accurately approximating the sine of 1 degree by showing it to be the solution of a cubic equation. These astronomers also calculated to length of a year accurate to about 25 seconds.
    </p>

  <p>
    Al-Kashi was aware of the following identities involving sine.
    <md>
      \sin 3 \alpha = 3 \sin \alpha - 4 \sin^3 \alpha
    </md>
    and

    <md>
      \sin 3^{\circ} = 0.052335956
    </md>
    
  </p>

  <p>
    By letting <m>\alpha = 1</m>, he obtained the equation
    <md>
      \sin^3 1^{\circ} -0.75\sin 1^{\circ} + 0.013083989 = 0.
    </md>
    This means that <m>\sin 1^{\circ}</m> is the solution to the cubic equation
    <md>
      x^3-0.75x+0.013083989=0
    </md>
    
  </p>

  <p>
    By solving this equation, Al-Kashi would be able to determine the value of <m>\sin 1^{\circ}</m>. Unfortunately, this equation is not easy to solve directly, so Al-Kashi needed to approximate the solution.
  </p>

  <p>
    Al-Kashi came up with an ingenious iterative method for finding the solution to this equation. We'll first demonstrate his method on the simpler equation <m>x^2-6x+8 = 0</m>
  </p>

  <p>
    First we can rearrange this equation as <m>x^2+8 = 6x</m> or <m>\dfrac{x^2}{6}+ \dfrac{8}{6} = x</m>. 
  </p>

  <p>
    <m>f(x) = \dfrac{x^2}{6}+ \dfrac{8}{6}</m>. Then we have the equation <m>f(x) = x</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    We now choose an initial guess <m>x_0</m> and compute <m>f(x_0)</m>. If our initial guess is good enough, <m>f(x_0)</m> will be a better approximation than <m>x_0</m>. So we let <m>x_1 = f(x_0)</m>. Then <m>f(x_1)</m> is a better approximation than <m>x_1</m> so let <m>x_2 = f(x_1)</m>. In general let <m>x_n = f(x_{n-1})</m>. This gives us a sequence of increasingly better approximations, <m>x_0, x_1, x_2, \ldots, x_n</m>. By taking the sequence sufficiently far, we can approximate the solution of the equation. 
  </p>

  <p>
    Let <m>x_0 = 1</m>. Then <m>f(1) = \dfrac{9}{6} = x_1</m>. Further iteration gives us the sequence
    <md>
      <mrow> x_0 \amp = 1 </mrow>
      <mrow> x_1 \amp = \frac{9}{6}</mrow>
      <mrow> x_2 \amp = 1.71 </mrow>
      <mrow> x_3 \amp = 1.82 </mrow>
      <mrow> x_4 \amp = 1.885 </mrow>
      <mrow> x_5 \amp = 1.925 </mrow>
      <mrow> x_6 \amp = 1.95 </mrow>
    </md>
    
  </p>

  <p>
    From these approximations it appears that the solution is <m>x=2</m>, which is one solution to the equation <m>x^2-6x+8 =0</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Now we use this approach to solve
    <md>
      x^3-0.75x + 0.013083989 = 0
    </md>
    
  </p>

  <p>
    First we rearrange the equation by getting <m>x</m> by itself. This gives
    <md>
      \dfrac{4}{3}x^3 + 0.0174453187=x.
    </md>
    Let <m>f(x) = \dfrac{4}{3}x^3 + 0.0174453187</m>, so <m>f(x) = x</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Since <m>\sin 1^{\circ}</m> is very small, let's guess that <m>x_0 = 0</m>. This gives the following sequence.
    <md>
      <mrow> x_0 \amp = 0.0174453187 </mrow>
      <mrow> x_1 \amp = 0.0174523977578 </mrow>
      <mrow> x_2 \amp = 0.0174524063791 </mrow>
      <mrow> x_3 \amp = 0.0174524063896 </mrow>
    </md>
    This converges very quickly and after 3 iterations we already have a high degree of accuracy for <m>\sin 1^{\circ}</m>. The actual value is <m>0.0174524064373</m>, so we have 9 decimal places of accuracy. Al-Kashi continued this process to achieve 16 decimal places of accuracy.
  </p>



  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-Number-Theory">
    <title>Number Theory</title>

    <p>
      Number theory is a branch of mathematics devoted to the study of the properties of the integers. The classification of integers into even and odd or prime and composite are examples of number theory as are theorems such as the sum of two odd numbers is an even number and Euclid's method for finding perfect numbers. Both the ancient Greek and ancient Indian mathematicians came up with many results of number theory. The mathematicians of the Islamic world built on these foundations and extended these ideas. 
    </p>

    <p>
      A remarkable example of number theory in the Islamic world is found in the works of Thabit ibn Qurra, a ninth century Arab astronomer and mathematician who was a member of a religious group called the Sabeans of Harran which worshipped the stars. His <em>Book on the Determination of Amicable Numbers</em> considers the properties of <term>amicable number pairs</term>. Amicable number pairs are pairs of numbers for which the sum of proper divisors of the first totals the second and the sum of proper divisors of the second totals the first. For example <m>220</m> and <m>284</m> are amicable numbers since the proper factors of <m>220</m> are
      <md>
        1+2+4+5+10+11+20+22+44+55+110 = 284
      </md>
      and the proper factors of <m>284</m> are
      <md>
        1+2+4+71+142 = 220.
      </md>
      
    </p>

    <p>
      Amicable numbers had been considered by Ancient Greek mathematicians but they failed to derive any of them. Thabit ibn Qurra provided the following rule for finding amicable pairs.
    </p>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-Thabit">
      <title>Construction of Amicable Pairs</title>
      
      
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>p = 3\cdot 2^n-1</m>, <m>q = 3 \cdot 2^{n-1}-1</m> and <m>r = 9 \cdot 2^{2n-1}-1</m> are all prime numbers, then <m>M = 2^npq</m> and <m>N = 2^n r</m> for amicable pairs. 
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

    <p>
      As an example, if <m>n = 2</m> then <m>p = 11</m>, <m>q = 5</m>, and <m>r = 71</m> are all prime numbers. Hence <m>M = 2^2 \cdot 11 \cdot 5 = 220</m> and <m>N = 2^2 \cdot 71 = 284</m> are amicable numbers.
    </p>

    <p>
      Another contributor to number theory was Abu Bakr al-Karaji, a tenth-century Iranian mathematician from the city of Karaj near Tehran. In one of his works he considered binomial expansion. He correctly determined the rule of the binomial coefficients <m>C_n^k</m> in the expansion
      <md>
        (a+b)^n = \sum_{k=0}^n C_n^k a^{n-k}b^k
      </md>
      namely that <m>C_n^k = C_{n-1}^{k-1} C_{n-1}^k</m>.
      
    </p>

    <p>
      A later Iranian mathematician Al-Samaw'al created a table of these binomial coefficients and discussed how to create such a table.
    </p>

    <blockquote>
      <p>
        Let us now recall a principle for knowing the necessary number of multiplications of these degrees by each other, for any number divided into two parts. al-Karaji said that in order to succeed we must place <q>one</q> on a table and <q>one</q> below the first <q>one</q>, move the [first] <q>one</q> into another column, add the [first] <q>one</q> to he one below it. We thus obtain <q>two</q>, which we put below the [transferred] <q>one</q> and we place the [second] <q>one</q> below <q>two</q>. We have therefore <q>one</q>, <q>two</q>, and <q>one</q>. This shows that for every number composed of two numbers, if we multiply each of them by itself once -- since the two extremes are <q>one</q> and <q>one</q> -- and if we multiply each one by the other twice -- since the intermediary term is <q>two</q> -- we obtain the square of this number. If we then transter the <q>one</q> in the second column into another column, then add <q>one</q> [from the second column] to <q>two</q> [below it], we obtain <q>three</q> to be written under the <q>one</q> [in the third column], if we then add <q>two</q> (from the second column) to <q>one</q> below it, we have <q>three</q> which is written under <q>three</q>, then we write <q>one</q> under this <q>three</q>; we thus obtain a third column whose numbers are <q>one</q>, <q>three</q>, <q>three</q>, and <q>one</q>. This teaches us that the cube of any number composed of two numbers is given by the sum of the cube of each of them and three times the product of each of them by the square of the other.
      </p>
    </blockquote>

    <p>
      Al-Samaw'al continued in this manner until he had constructed a table of binomial coefficients up to the twelfth power. Such a table is known today as <term>Pascal's triangle</term> after its appearance in Blaise Pascal's book <em>Traite du Triangle Arithmetique</em> in 1665. However it had appeared in Western literature before then. A table of binomial coefficients appeared in Michael's Stifel's book <em>Deutsche Arithmetica</em> published in 1544. Pascal's triangle was also independently discovered by Chinese mathematicians.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      Al-Karaji also determined formulas for the sums of the first <m>n</m> squares and cubes.
    </p>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-al-karaj">
      <title>Sums of Squares and Cubes</title>
      
      
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>n</m> be a positive integer. Then
          <md>
            1^2+2^2+3^2+ \ldots + n^2 = (\frac{2n}{3}+\frac{1}{3})(1+2+3+ \ldots + n)
          </md>
          and
          <md>
            1^3+2^3+3^3 + \ldots + n^3 = (1+2+3+\ldots + n)^2
          </md>
          
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    

    <p>
      al-Samaw'al further simplified these identities by showing that
      <md>
        1^2+2^2+3^2+ \ldots + n^2 = \frac{1}{6}n(n+1)(2n+1)
      </md>
      and

      <md>
        1^3+2^3+3^3 + \ldots + n^3 = \frac{1}{4}(n(n+1))^2
      </md>
      
      
    </p>

    <p>
      al-Karaji's proof for the sum of cubes is the earliest known use of mathematical induction. He only gives the proof for the case of <m>n=10</m> but the proof applies to any value of <m>n</m>.
    </p>

    <proof>
      <p>
        al-Karaji begins with a square with side lengths <m>1+2+3+ \ldots + 10</m>, which is partitioned as shown below.
      </p>

<figure>
      <caption>Square used in al-Karaji's proof of the sum of cubes formula</caption>
      <image source="squares.png" width="50%">
        <description>Diagram showing a sequence of nested squares sharing the same lower-left corner DDD. The largest square has vertices AAA (upper left), BBB (upper right), CCC (lower right), and DDD (lower left). Along the left side of the large square, points EEE and HHH mark the top edges of two smaller nested squares. The vertical distances on the left side are labeled 111, 222, 999, and 101010 from bottom to top, indicating successive square side lengths.
Inside the large square is a square of side length 101010 with top-left corner at EEE and top-right corner FFF; its lower-right corner is GGG on the bottom edge of the large square. Inside that is a square of side length 999 with top-left corner at HHH and top-right corner III; its lower-right corner is JJJ on the bottom edge. Two additional smaller squares of side lengths 222 and 111 are nested in the lower-left corner. All squares are aligned with the coordinate directions, and each smaller square shares the same lower-left corner DDD as the larger squares.
        </description>
      </image>
    </figure>




      <p>
        The outermost L shaped region <m>ABCGFE</m> is made up of two rectangles and a square. Thus it has area equal to <m>2\cdot 10(1+2+3+ \ldots + 9) + 10^2</m> which simplifies to <m>9\cdot 10^2+ 10^2 = 10^3</m>. Similarly the area of the next region <m>EFGJIH</m> has area <m>9^3</m>. We continue in like manner until we reach the single square in the bottom left corner with area <m>1</m>. Thus the total area of the square is <m>1^3+2^3+3^3 + \ldots + n^3</m>. Alternative the area of the square is the square of the length of its side or <m>(1+2+3+\ldots + 10)^2</m> which proves the theorem. 
      </p>


    </proof>


    
  </subsection>





  </section>